Very fast  growing on  almost any  degraded soil  (pH 3-9).  Needs full  sun.  Fuelwood,  erosion  control,  shade, weed  surppresssent . Scarify by  immersion in  boiling water  for two  minutes  before  planting.
Open- pollinated,  prolific
producer of  dark green  spineless  pods which  can be  harvested  continuously  for weeks.  Pods best  when 2-3  inches long.  Plants grow  4-5 feet in  height on  average. 52  days.

Plant is early  and vigorous  with small  parted leaves.  Fruit-set  begins on the  7th-8th node  when it is  sown under  high  temperature  conditions  (30-35  degrees C)  and on the 4th  node when it  is sown under  lower  temperatures  (about  20  degrees C).  Fruit is plump,  dark green,  and  five-ridged.
Acacia - a  great forage  species. Used  as organic  matter and in  alley cropping.  Potential
source of fuel  wood and  fodder.  Tolerates acid  soil. Greater  than 1000mm  mean annual  rainfall  needed to  grow well.

This variety of  okra  has an  unusual  lance-shaped  leaf which  allows sunlight  and rain to  pass through  the leaf  canopy and  reach the  growing plant.  Harvesting  from overhead  is  considerably  easier due to  leaf  morphology.

Seed flour can  make up to  25% of a  recipe. Fix  nitrogen,  produce  timber for light  construction  or firewood,  used as  windbreak and  low-grade  fodder.  Survive hot,  dry conditions  (40C, 200mm  annual  rainfall); plant  10m apart,  closer if  rainfall  >450mm  annuallly.
Very fast  growing on  acid,
degraded  soils, needs  full sun to sun.  Fuelwood,  suppresses  weeds. Not  drought or  wind tolerant,  not for fodder.  Don't coppice.  Scarify the  seeds before  planting.
African  deciduous  tree 20-30m  tall. Adapted  to hot dry  climates.  Leaves used  for animal  fodder. Soak  seeds  overnight in  hot water  before sowing.

A medium to  large-sized  tree ranging  from 6-15m in  height. Plant  in full sun, and  in frost free  locations.  Seed must be  scarified  (scratched) or  boiled for 60  seconds to  germinate.  Wood used for  furniture.  Seeds used  as beads for  necklaces and  ornaments.

at 33-40  degrees  latitude.
Short day.  Open  pollinated. 95  days. Smooth  glossy skin  that is  purplish-red in  color. White  sweet flesh.  Good for  storage.

Short day  grano type  Hybrid. Very  high yielding  white onion  with good skin  quality.
Native to  moist, low  elevation
places. Good  green manure  forage. Min of  1000 mm rain.  Good in low  areas or  drainage  ditches.
An open  pollinated  short day  variety. 187  days. It has  red flesh,  tough outer  scales and  stores well.  Flattened  globe shape  bulbs.
Intermediate  day OPEN  POLLINATED  type. 95 days.  Large, white  globe with firm  flesh. Fair  keeper.
Intermediate  day, open  pollinated  type. 95 days.  Large, white  globe with firm  flesh. Fair  keeper.

125 days. A  biennial,  onion-like  crop, leeks  don't form  bulbs and  leaves are flat  and large.  A  more mild  taste than  onions, leeks  are used in  soups and  similar dishes.   Sow at less  than 1/2-inch  depth, or sow  in flats and  transplant.  Plant during  cooler season.
Also called  Chinese leek,  and garlic  chives. Mild,
garlic-flavored  leaves. Grow  in full sun and  high organic  matter. Cut  leaves to 1"  above ground  to harvest  periodically.
Also called  slender  amaranth.  Annual green  leaf vegetable.  0.5m hieght.  Sow seeds in  well-drained  composted  soil 1 cm  deep. Plant in  full sun.
Large, white  globes with  single centers  and firm, mild  flesh. Stores  well. Long day  type. 120 days  to harvest.  Open  pollinated.
Short day  grano type  hybrid.  Uniform, late  maturing,  tolerant to  pink root.  Round-high  round shape.
Likes cool  weather with  moist, well  drained soil.  Cease  watering when  85% of seed  heads are  golden. Plan 5  in. apart.
Germination is  difficult. Try  alternating 8  hr of light at  30C with 16 hr  of dark at  20C, in a  moist towel.  Plant 2-3 Cm  deep.  Innoculate
with proper  bacteria  before  planting. High  quality legume  for forage and  orchard  ground cover.  Shade  tolerant.
Plant 1/8 inch  deep, thin to 6  inches apart.   Watch for  lodging. Grain  eaten or  ground into  flour. Leaves  eaten as  spinach or  salad.
From Mexico.  Start seeds  1/4 inch deep  (in plots, or  direct seed)  and thin to 4-6  apart in rows.
A dark green,  strong, tall  and aromatic  annual plant.  Sow seeds in  well-drained  composted  soil 1cm deep.  plant out into  full sun in  rows 30cm  (12") apart.
From Mexico.  Start seeds  1/4 inch deep  (in plots, or  direct seed)  and thin to 4-6  apart in rows.
Deep red  flowers, grain  type. Start  seeds 1/4 inch  deep (in plots,  or direct seed)  and thin to 4-6  apart in rows.
Plant at a  shallow depth,  maintain moist  seed bed.  Cook and eat
young leaves  like spinach;  good yields of  yellow grain.
Similar to  tigerleaf  amaranth. The  ornamental  leaves are  eaten as a  warm-weather  spinach. Sow  seeds 1cm  deep in  well-drained  soil. Thin to  20cm apart in  rows.
Plant 1/8 inch  deep thin to 6  inches apart.  Susceptible to  lodging. Cook  leaves and  young stems;  eats like  spinach.
From Taiwan.  Plant 1/4"  deep, 6" apart.  Cook leaves  and young  stems; eat like  spinach.
Sow seeds  1/2" deep,  about 8" apart  in fertile soil.  Prefers trellis.  Heat-tolerant.  Leaves eaten  raw or  cooked.
For firewood,  green manure,  animal forage,  erosion  control,  flowers for  bees. Treat  seeds with hot  water, then  soak in cold  water 48  hours before  planting.
Drought  resistant,  green manure  and cover
crop. Young  leaves and  immature  pods eaten  after boiling to  remove toxins.  Also used as  fodder.

Sow seeds  1/2-1" deep,  about 8" apart  in fertile soil.  Prefers trellis.  Heat- tolerant.  Leaves eaten  raw or  cooked.

72-75 days to  maturity. Fruit  reaches 3" in  length and  1.5" in  diameter.  Fruits are dark  green to red.  Pungent with  thick walls;  upright plants.  (Scoville  rating of  3500-6000).  Open  pollinated.

60 days to  harvest. Dark  red-colored  root. Edible  greens are  high in iron.  Open- pollinated.

Plant 1-2 ft.  Apart.  Prefers  colder  temperatures,  but will  tolerate heat.

Leaves and  petioles used  for pickling  and stir-frying.   Can withstand  both cold and  hot climates.   Slow to bolt,  resistant to  soft rot and  virus.  Plants  can be  harvested as  early as 20  days after  transplanting.
Tropical vining  plant. Fruit  much like a  cucumber.  Plant 2 cm  deep in well  drained,  composted  soil.

Tomate de  arbol. Meduim  perennial  shrub/ short  tree (10-15 ft  tall).  Tree  with delicious  red, amber or  yellow fruits  suitable for  juice, jams  and  preserves.  Plant about  1cm deep.  Hardy to  about 30  degrees F.  Self- pollinating.
Good slicing  cucumber.  Bears mid to  late summer.  Hybrid.
Large, high  dome,  semi-erect  variety that  takes 65 days  to reach  maturity.   Widely  adapted and  easy to grow.   Heavy,  attractive  heads. Hybrid.
Eat boiled  leaves like  spinach. Plant  after last frost  - sow seed  1/8" deep, thin  to 12-18"  apart in rich or  organic soil.
About 68 days  to maturity.  Fruit is  cylindrical with  some taper  ends and has  uniform dark  green color.  Plant is  monoecious
with compact  vines.  Resistant/  tolerant to  cucumber  mosaic virus,  downy  mildew,  powdery  mildew and  scab. Open  pollinated.
Eat boiled  leaves like  spinach. Plant  after last frost  - sow seed  1/8" deep, thin  to 12-18"  apart in rich or  organic soil.

Tightly packed  leaves make  extra-solid,  heavy, round  heads that  average 7 to  10 lbs. A  storage type  with  unequalled  keeping  qualities.  Crisp and  tender with  excellent  flavor. Use  fresh for  salads and  slaw.
Plant 3-4  seeds about  1cm deep on  composted  soil mounds  1m apart.  Grows  vigorously in  hot weather.
Eat boiled  leaves like  spinach. Plant  after last frost  - sow seeds  1/8" deep, thin  to 12-18"  apart in rich  organic soil.

2.6 Kg) with  thick skin that  turns  yellow-orange  when ripe  (good to ship;  e.g. preferred  in US  markets). Fruit  set 35cm  above ground;  grow well in  presence of  Ring Spot  virus.

Very uniform  in size, shape  and maturity.  Semi-Flat  Globe Shape.  Blue-Green in  color.  80-85  Days to  maturity.  Very  high packout  percentage  relates to  heavy yields.
Heat and cold  tolerance.   Bright  blue-green,  3-4 lb, round  heads.
Vigorous,  resists hot,  humid  weather.   Plant 3-4  seeds about  1/2" deep on  mounds  several feet
apart.
Good for all  season  (spring,  summer, or  fall).  Deep  purple-red,  4-5 lbs  globe-shaped  heads.

Soak seeds  overnight.  Plant in large  pots 5 mm  deep in  well-mixed  topsoil,  compost, sand  (1:1:2). Keep  moist and  shaded.  Transplant at  30cm to well  drained soil,  full sun.  Self- pollinating.

Plant about  one inch deep  in hills 3ft  apart.  Vigorous  growth-- will  sprawl over  large areas.

Plants are  medium,  forming heads  very early, can  be harvested  50 days after  transplanting.   Heads are  elliptical, solid  and uniform.   About 4  pounds with  tender texture.   Hybrid  suitable for  growing in  warm  weather.
Red fleshed  fruit averaging

1.5-2.0 kg.  Good  sweetness.  Sets fruit on at  average 70  cm above soil  and is tolerant  to Papaya  Ring Spot  Virus (PRSV).  Produces fruit  on average 9  months from  seed. Soak  seeds  overnight.  Plant in large  pots 5mm  deep in  well-mixed  topsoil,  compost, sand  (1:1:2). Keep  moist and  shaded.  Transplant at  30 cm to well  drained soil.  full sun. Self  pollinating.

Plant 1cm  deep in  well-drained  composted  soil. Grows  2-3' tall, is  erect and  spreading with  many large,  undulated  leaves on a  white stem.   Withstands  cold as well as  heat, and  adverse soil  conditions.  A  high yeilding  hardy type of  excellent  quality.
Heavy yielding  oval pumpkin  with dark,  thick flesh.  Rich flavor.
Large fruits,  8-40 pounds,  tender deep  golden-orange  flesh with high  sugar content.
Needs long  warm growing  season.

About 43 to  days to  maturity;  squash deep  golden yellow  in color and  reaches 5.5-6  inches in  length and is  semi- crookneck  shape; plant is  open,  vigorous bush.  Consistent  yields of  smooth  skinned fruit.  Hybrid.
A variety with  a high yield  potential.  A  widely  adaptable  collard.   Grows up to  23 inches tall.   Has a good  regrowth after  cutting.
Likes to climb  4-5 feet. Very  drought- tolerant  kegume used  as green  manure,  fodder. Small  leaves; not a  thick  groundcover.  Bright purple  flowers used  as dye.
About 55 days  to maturity;  blue-green  color with  finely curled  leaves;  uniform  selection and  standard  variety.  Open  Pollinated.
Grown in high  temperatures  with high
humidity at  low altitudes.  A short-day  plant.
Glossy dark  green, erect  leaves with  broad white  stalks.   Uniform and  slow bolting.   Well adapted  with high yield  potential.
Large seeded  garbanzo  bean. Seeds  can be eaten  as a dry bean  or as a green  vegetable  when  immature.  Drought- tolerant
Normally used  as a forage  plant, edible  greens and  tuber.  Also  can be used  for a ground  cover if  broadcasted.
Deep green,  braod leaves.  A favorite  slow-bearing  strain.  High  yields,  attractive  leaves. 60  days to  maturity.

Early  maturing,  shorter  variety. Plant  2-4" apart.  High protein  chilean var.  Day-neutral.  Made into  flour or used  like rice.  Leaves eaten  cooked or  raw. Drought  tolerant, likes  cool temp.
Open- pollinated  variety. Grown  for greens.  Leaf is cut and  medium dark  green. 45  days.
Best adapted  to light  textured soils.  At least 600  mean annual  rainfall is  required. Soak  for 24 hours  before  planting.
Requires high  temps for  growth. Seeds  need to be  scarified.  Wide soil  adaptation,  700-1500mm  rain, early  flowering. Arid  region native,  can take  seasonal  flooding.
Annual herb.  Good green  manure. Bark  used as a  source of  fiber. Mildly  toxic to cattle.  Dry pods  scare mokeys  out of  gardens. Plant  1/2-1" deep.

Fast-growing  shrub or tree.  Produces  nutritious  fodder.  Tolerates a  wide range of  temperatures.  Does best in  sandy soil.  Scarify seed  or boil for 1  minute before  planting. Don't  disturb roots  when  transplanting.
Excellent  toxin-free  forage,  green- manure;  deters weevil  damage of  corn and rice.  Plant 1/2"-1"  deep.

About 85 days  to maturity;  Fruit is  near-round,  16"x14", 25  pounds; rind is  medium green  with dark  green stripes.  Flesh is  crimson red  and very  sweet. Good  long distance  shipper.  Resistant/toler ant to  Anthracnose  and Fusarium  Wilt. Open  pollinated.

Slicing  cucumber.  Early to  harvest, high  yields with  uniform dark  green color  that holds  well. 56 days  to maturity,  cylindricalbloc ky shape.  Resistant to  anthracnose  2, angular leaf  spot,  cucumber  mosiac virus,  powdery  mildew and  scab. Hybrid
An early  variety  producing  roots 8-9" long  with excellent  color and  smoothness.  Resistant to  alternaria and  cercospora
(causes  foliage  dieback).  Performs well  under heat  stress and  frost. Hybrid.

An early  variety  producing  roots 8-9" long  with excellent  color and  smoothness.  Resistant to  alternaria and  cercospora  (causes  foliage  dieback).  Performs well  under heat  stress and  frost. Hybrid.
Tropical carrot  variety which  sets seed in  one year.  Harvest crop  before seeds  set, but allow  a few plants to  go to seed.  Sow shallowly  and thin as  needed.
A midseason  variety that is  durable, bolt  hardy, and  has strong  tops. A  multi-purpose  carrot that is  7-8" long.  Very  productive.
Small thorny  deciduous  tree: 12-15 m  tall. Tolerates  acidic soil up  to 4 pH, and  rainfall from  1500-4000mm  per year. Tree  grows from  sea level to  1800m. Can  be used for  living fence,
fodder, wind  break, or crop  shade. Scarify  seed coat or  soak before  planting.

Important  grain crop.  Does best in  coll, moist  temperate  regions.  Tolerates  tropics at high  elevations.  Plant at 1"  deep, 6-7"  apart. Will not  flower well in  heat. Turn in  to build soil.

Important  grain crop.  Does best in  coll, moist  temperate  regions.  Tolerates  tropics at high  elevations.  Plant at 1"  deep, 6-7"  apart. Will not  flower well in  heat. Turn in  to build soil.
Used in alley  farming,  fodder,  fuelwood,  green manure,  mulch. Min.  rainfall  1500mm. can  survive long  dry spells.  Acid tollerant,  somewhat  shade  tolerant,  prefers clay  soils.
The grain is  used for bread  making.  Grows 3 feet  tall and takes  four months to  mature.
Can reach a  height of 150

feet.  Red  bark on young  growth.  Very  drought  resistant.   Wood is light  or deep red in  color.  Native  to Australia.   Soak in water  for 24 hours.   Sow 1/16  inches deep.   Keep soil  moist. Good  for saline and  alkaline soils
Annual tufted  grass, grains  very small.  Early  weeding, and  consistant  weeding is  required for  good yield.

Nitrogen fixing  tree. Highly  preferred for  SALT  technique in  Philippines.   Suffers during  extended  drought. Used  as fodder.  Sow seeds in  well-drained  compost  before  transplanting  into field.
Perennial  legume, grow  with common  permanent  grasses for  high quality  pasture.
Flowers in  short days.  perennial,  35-50" tall.  Rain tolerates  poorly  drained, acidic  soils. Dehull  for better  germination.
Aggressive,  persistent,
N-fixing shrub.  Tolerates  heavy grazing.  Scarify seeds  pre-planting;  pour boiling  water over  seeds and let  cool for 12  hours. Keep  soil moist after  planting.
Nick before  sowing. Seeds  should have  boiling water  poured over  them followed  by soaking in  room temp  water for 24  hours. Plant  seeds 1.5-2  cm deep.
Small, drought  resistant  grain. Seeds  milled for  flour. Plant  1/4" deep, full  sun.

Produces vivid  green edible  pods which  can be used  as a vegetable  when picked  green. High  yielding, many  pods contain  three seeds.  Plant 6-10  seeds per  foot, with  12-20"  between rows.  Harvest pods  when plump.  Productive,  early maturing  variety.
Produces vivid  green edible  pods which  can be used  as a vegetable  when picked  at the green  shell stage.  This variety  grows well in
sub-tropical  climates and  is very prolific.  Plant 6-10  sees per foot,  with 12-20"  between rows.
Braxton  variety  developed  specifically for  temperate  regions.

Nick seed  before  planting and  soak in cool  water  overnight.  Nitrogen fixing  tree used in  alley cropping,  as a living  fence, shade,  fuelwood, and  fodder.  Flowers can  be cooked  and eaten.  Press seed  lightly into soil;  cover with  2-4mm of soil.

Outstanding  variety from  Guatemala  known for high  leaf and wood  production.  Nitrogen fixing  tree used in  alley cropping,  living fences,  shade,  fuelwood, and  fodder.  Flowers can  be cooked  and eaten.  Press seed  lightly into soil  and cover with  2-4cm of soil.
Nematode  resistant  tropical  soybean  developed by  the University  of Hawaii.
Produces

deep green  edible pods  with light  green  pubescence.  Can be used  as a vegetable  when picked  green. Plant  6-10 seeds  per foot with  12-20"  between rows.  Harvest pods  when plump.  Productive,  early maturity  variety ready  in 75 days.
Used for  shade,  windbreaks,  timber,  fuelwood,  alley cropping.  Thrives in  tropical to  sub-tropical  conditions.  Adaptable to  wide range of  rainfall. Grows  best in loamy  soil.
Seeds  processed for  oil. Also grown  as fodder,  forage, green  manure.  Seeds and  heads after  thrashing fed  to livestock.  Not for wet  tropics. Can  tolerate arid  climates, and  some frost.
Grown  commercially  for cooking oil,  bird food,  human food  and an  excellent  poultry and  rabbit food.  Grows 5 feet  tall or more  with large  disc-shaped
flower heads.  Mature seeds  can be shelled  and eaten.
75-80 days.  Strong stalks  grow up to 4  m (12 ft) high  with large  bright yellow  heads.  Confection  sunflower with  large edible  seeds.
110 days. A  Russian strain  grown  commercially  for the  pressing of  quality oil for  salads or  cooking.  Small, black  shelled seeds  also make  excellent  poultry, rabbit  or wild bird  feed.

Large tree up  to 45-60 m tall  with long  straight trunk  and enormous  rounded  canopy of  glossy foliage.  Grows best at  0-1000m in  moist,  well-drained  soils. It is frost  sensitive.  Important  timber  species. Soak  in cold water  for 48 hours  before sowing.
Attractive  annual shrub,  also known as  False Roselle.  Use leaves in  salads, flower  calyxes (when  closed) used  to color juices,  sauces and
jellies. Plant in  spring in  deep, loose  soil. 1 m  apart, 1 cm  deep.

Late-blooming  variety;  blooms late  August/Septe mber in N.  America. Plant  used as a  source of fiber  for paper.  Annual crop.  Soak seeds  before  planting for  better  germination.  Plant 2 cm  deep in  composted,  well drained  soil.
Annual crop.  Resistant to  rootknot  nematodes  and soil-borne  fungi.  Intolerant of  frost, needs  well-drained  soils. Can be  used as a  fiber source  for paper.

Also called  "Florida  cranberry"  Fresh calyx  (fleshy  structure after  the flower has  fades) used in  beverages,  sauces and  salads.  Leaves are  also edible.  Plant 1/2" (1  cm) deep and  3 feet apart.
Excellent  ground cover  or green  manure; may  reduce  root-knot
nematodes.   Hairy-stemed  plant grows  2-4 feet. Sow  at 10-15  lbs/acre  before rainy  season.

Shrub or tree  up to 6 m tall.  Oil in the seed  can be used  for candles,  soaps and  bio-diesel  production.  Planted as a  living fence  and to reduce  erosion.  Establishes  easily from  cuttings and is  drought  resistant.  WARNING:  seeds and  plant are  TOXIC to  humans.

Shrub or tree  up to 6m tall.  Oil in the seed  can be used  for candles,  soaps and  bio-diesel  production.  Planted as a  living fence  and to reduce  erosion.  Establishes  easily from  cuttings and is  drought  resistant.  WARNING:  seeds and  plant TOXIC  to humans.
Drought  resistant  green manure  cover crop  usually relay  cropped with  maize. Mature  seeds are  edible. From  Thailand,  were sold and
processed as  a snack food.
Selected for  early  flowering, high  seed yielding  ability and dry  matter  production.  Good forage  and ground  cover. Does  well in humid  regions but is  fairly drought  resistant as  well.

Mix of Lablab  varieties,  white, highworth, rongai. Does  well in humid  regions but is  fairly drought  resistant as  well. Plant 1 "  deep, 6" apart  near a trellis,  pole , or  fence. Eat  young and  tendet pods or  cook dried  seeds.  Drought- tolerant forage  & green cover  crop.

Tropical  twining vine  with purple  foliage and  purple stems.  Completely  edible seeds,  young leaves,  and flowers.  thrives in  warm  weather.  Planting depth  1/2 to 1". Final  plant spacing  12-18"
Lablab is an  excellent  forage and  ground cover.  Does well in  humid regions
but is fairly  drought  resistent as  well.
Lablab is an  excellent  forage and  ground cover.  Does well in  humid regions  but is fairly  drought  resistant as  well.
Erect annual  herb with  bright yellow  flowers. Eat  leaves in  mixed green  salads. grows  well in hot  sun. Plant  seeds 1/4"  deep
Heat-resistant,  forms heads  in fertile soil  with adequate  moisture and  shade. Plant  1' apart for  lettuce, closer  for leaf.
Good  uniformity and  heat  tolerance,  slow to bolt.  Tolerant to  downy  mildew,  lettuce mosiac  virus and  topburn. 65  days. Plant  9-12 inches  apart.
An early red  Leaf variety  with deep red  frilly leaves.  large sized  head. Widely  adaptable.  Excellent  color. Good  uniformity and  weight, not as  brittle. Slow  bolting. Plant
9-12 inches  apart.
Bibb lettuce  which forms a  deep green  head with  thick, soft,  smooth  leaves. Slow  bolting with  tender leaves  on a medium  sized frame.  65 Days plant  9-12 inches  apart.
Romaine  lettuce with  dark green  blistered  leaves.

Provides  gourds the  size of bushel  baskets grown  on a vigorous  vine. fruits  edible only  when small.  leaves and  young shoots  used as  potherbs.  Seed yields  an oil used in  cooking,  vegetable  curd can be  made from the  seeds.

A drought  tolerant  legume used  for forage.  Seeds can be  roasted and  eaten in  porridge or  bread.  Caution: if  eaten it large  quantities  grasspea may  cause a type  of paralysis  known as  athyrism. This  accession is a  mix of low  toxin  selections
from ICARDA
Pulse crop  domesticated  in the Middle  East. Adapted  to low rainfall.  tall, upright  habit. Early  blooming  date. Good  yield. Good for  arid and  semi-arid  areas.
Grain lugume;  high in protein  and oil.  Usually grown  between  1800-4000m.  semi-hardy;  some  resistanve to  frost;  drought- resistant. does  well on  marginal soils.  plant about 2  cm deep.
Fast growing,  leguminous  tree for  firewood,  forage, ect.  Suitable for  higher  alltitudes:  1000-2000ft  above sea  level. Scarify  ( nick and  soak  overnight)  before  planting.

Large,  beefsteak- type, 10 to 12  oz fruits have  10 times as  much as beta  carotine as  normal. very  low in acid,  Heavy  production of  3-1/2', nearly  globe-shaped,  smooth fruits.  Determinate,
full sun, 80  days to  maturity.

Good fuel  wood, shade  and organic  matter.  Suitable for  high alt. Does  best between  1000- 2000feet.  Highly Pysllid  resistant.  Scarify in very  hot water  overnight ( or  scratch coat  before  planting )
85 days to  maturity. An  old standard  variety with a  beautiful deep  red fruit that  has a superb  classic tomato  taste. Open  pollinated.
Fast growing  leguminous  tree,  firewood: forage. psyllid  resistant  variety.  Scarify by  soaking over  night or by  nicking seed  coat before  planting.
Develpoed by  U of Florida,  Resistant to  Verticillum  and Fusarium  Wilt, Races 1  & 2, and Gray  Leafspot.  Grow on  ground or  stake.
Open  pollinated  determinate  red roma.  75  days to  maturity. Sow  1 cm. deep.
Disease  Resistant.

Tomato  develped by  the University  of Florida that  tolerates heat  and humidity.  Produces firm,  red, medium-  to large-sized  fruit. Resistant  to Fusarium  wilt 9races 1,  2, and 30,  verticillium wilt  9race 10 and  gray leaf spot.
Fast grwoing  leguminous  tree. Hawaiian  giant type.  Produces  large  quantities of  seeds pods.  Scarify ( nick  or boil ) seed  coat before  planting. Plant  1 cm deep.
Hawaiian  Leucaena. A  leguminous  agroforestry  tree. Scarify  ( nick  seedcoat )  before  planting.
Large,  stake-type  variety; high  yileds.  Resistant to  verticillium,  Fusarium,  Grey Leaf  Spot,  Graywall,  Tobacco  Mosaic and  Leaf Molds.
Cross  between L.  pallida and L.  leucocephala  developed at  CTAHR- University of  Hawaii. This
varoety has 1.  Potential  self-sterility  ( seeless ) 2.  Pyslllid  resistenace 3.  Cold tolerance  4. Better  forage  production  than other L  ssp
75 days. An  excellent  varity  developed at  the Bradenton  experiment  station by Dr.  Walter. This  tomato is  resistant to  Fusarium Wilt  1&2, and to  Gray Leaf  Spot
Climbing vine.  Ridged fruit.  Eat as  vegetable  when young.  Use dried fruit  as sponge.  Grows well in  humid tropics.  plant about  1/2" deeo,  trellis or will  sprawl on  ground.
Pods shatter  readily.  perennial  suited to  30-70 in rain,  high temps  and droughts.  Can handle  steady  grazing.  palatable. ext  wide soil tol.  very versatile  and easy to  establish.
Drought  resistant, high  seedling vigor,  early  flowering,  needs good
drainage. Best  on 30-60  inches of rain  per year.  Sow  during rainy  season.
Use as a  covercrop or  green manure.  Requires short  day to flower.  Plant 1" deep.  Scarify (nick  seed coat)  before  planting. Very  vigorous  growth.
Small,  red-seeded  variety  harvested as  a dry bean,  4-5 months  from planting.  Resistant to  bean golden  yellow mosaic  virus. Top  performer in  field trials in  Haiti.

Reaches  maturity early;  fruit is globe  shaped and  2-3 oz; plant is  determinate  and yields a  larger  Mexican husk  tomatillo.  Open  pollinated.  Plant 1 cm  deep, in well  drained  potting mix.
Flowers in 90  days. Does  not require  short days to  bloom. Plant  1" deep. Use  as a cover  crop or green  manure.  Caution:  stinging hairs  on plants may  cause skin
irritation.
Delicious  succulent  4-inch edible  pods.  Produces  abundantly on  4-ft tall vines.  Needs trellis.  Pick 68 days  after sowing.  Open  pollinated.

Light green,  edible flat  pods. Snow  pea with mild  sweet flavor.  Smooth pod.  High yielding.  Resistance to  common wilt,  pea mosaic  virus, and  powdery  mildew. Pods  reach 4 inches  in length and  vine reaches  26-32 inches  in height.
Nick seeds  before  planting. Sow  seeds 1. 5-2cm deep.  Prefers heavy,  clay soils or  medium loamy  soils.  Tolerates  acidity.  Leaves, fruit  and seeds are  edible.
Vigorous and  somewhat  drought- tolerant green  manure cover  crop.  Bush-like,  compact  growth habit,  does not  produce as  many vines as  other  varieites. Do  NOT eat  beans -
TOXIC.  Short-day  plant.

Developed at  the University  of Georgia;  grazing  tolerant and  excellent hay  yielding.  Semi-dormant  alfalfa variety  that has a Fall  Dormancy  rating of 5.  Broad  spectrum pest  resistance.  High  resistance to  Fusarium Wilt;  resistant to  Phytophthora  root rot.

Very hard  wood,  durable,  resistant to  rotting. Used  for  construction  and hand  tools. Grows  in very dry  locations.  Bark is a  source of  tannin.  Flowers  important  source of  nectar for  bees.  Valuable in  dune  stabilization  and recovery  for degraded  soils.
High yield,  graze tolerant.  Can be  grazed heavily  and will thrive  so it can be  harvested for  hay later.  Great for  weight gain in  livestock.
Medium dark  green  commercial  variety with  uniform broad  leaves.  Slow  bolting.
6 1/2 inch  pods,  stringless,  fleshy and  flavorful.  Resistant to  common bean  mosaic and  powdery  mildew. Plant  in full sunlight,  1 inch deep in  rows, 2 inches  apart, thin to 4  inches.
Fancy, wide  leaf type with  broad,  smooth,  glossy leaves.  Makes for  attractive  bunches.

Hardy short  day plant  adapted to  dry, hot  conditions.  Disease- resistant,  high-yielding  lines. Not  frost-tolerant.  Rust, blight  resistant;  wilt-tolerant.  Plant 1/4"  deep at 4"  spacing. Avoid  overwatering.
Hardy short  day plant  adapted to  dry, hot  conditions.  Disease- resistant,  high-yielding  lines. Not  frost-tolerant.  Rust, blight  resistant;  wilt-tolerant.  Plant 1/4"
deep at 4"  spacing. Avoid  overwatering.

Hardy short  day plant  adopted to  dry, hot  conditions.  Disease- resistant,  high-yielding  lines. Not  frost-tolerant.  Rust, blight  resistant; wilt  tolerant. Plant  1/4" deep at 4"  spacing. Avoid  overwatering.

The shelled  beans (and  young pods)  are boiled and  used in soups  and stews.  Seeds are  also dried and  fermented into  tempeh kara.  The leaves  may be  steamed and  eaten,  although they  are often  bitter.
Bright  blue-green.   Aromatic and  flavorful.  Use  fresh or dried.

Hardy short  day plant  adopted to  dry, hot  conditions.  Disease- resistant,  high-yielding  lines. Not  frost-tolerant.  Rust, blight  resistant; wilt  tolerant. Plant  1/4" deep at 4"  spacing. Avoid  overwatering.

Indeterminate,  very  deep-rooted,  with tolerance  to heat and  low humidity,  but high water  demand till  root depth is  12-18". Nick  and soak seed  overnight;  then plant no  more than 2"  deep, and  keep seedbed  moist.

Indeterminate,  very  deep-rooted,  with tolerance  to heat and  low humidity,  but high water  demand till  root depth is  12-18". Nick  and soak seed  overnight;  then plant no  more than 2"  deep, and  keep seedbed  moist.
Indeterminate.  Nick and oak  sed overnight  before  planting. Plant  spacing  10-12". Best if  irrigated, but  will tolerate  some drought.
Sow seeds 6"  apart, 1" deep  after frost.  Produces  edible roots in  short days.  Harvest roots  as needed but  before new  growth. Eat  like water  chestnuts.  Mature  pods/seeds  are toxic.
Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep near  trellis. Grows  well in poor  soil with little  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked; eat  leaves  cooked.
Matures 17-26  weeks.  Fast-growing  legume. Cold  tolerant. Plant  5-6" apart.  Used as  forage, hay  plant, and soil  improver  (N-fixer); sow  in fall to  harvest in  spring.
Plant about  7"apart.  Must  have water  until 6" high.  Goes dormant  in drought.  Cut
seedheads a  few days  before ripe so  birds don't eat  them.

Perennial  warm-climate,  tropical.  Can't  tolerate long  dry seasons.  Fast-growing.  Plant 5-6"  apart. Used as  forage, hay  plant, and soil  improver  (N-fixer); plant  as  cool-season  legume.
Short, very  leafy, immune  to rust & leaf  spot; grows in  infertile soil;  lacks prussic  acid &  glucoside.  Used strictly  for FORAGE-  not a grain
crop. Not  resistant to  downey  mildew.
Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep near  trellis. Grows  well in poor  soil with little  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked. Eat  leaves  cooked.

A fairly  slow-growing  shrub or small  tree, the  cattley guava  generally  ranges from  6.5 to 14 feet  tall, but the  yellow-fruited  may attain 40  ft.

Medium-sized  fava tolerates  cold  temperatures.  Can produce  4000-6000  lb/acre dry  matter and  100-200  lb/acre N.  Plant 100-150  lb/acre or 3  lb/1000 sq. ft.  Plants grow to  6 ft and  produce an  abundance of  small,  good-tasting  favas of the
cover crop  kind.
Soak seeds  overnight.  Cover with  1/4" soil, keep  moist. Cold,  heat, drought  and poor soil  tolerant  legume. Slow  growth but  hardy.
Short, very  leafy, immune  to rust & leaf  spot; grows in  infertile soil;  lacks prussic  acid &  glucoside. Dry  seeds used to  make flour.

Sprawling  annual, mat  protects soil.  23% protein.  Drought  tolerant;  needs full sun.  Prefers having  compost  added before  planting. Plant  seeds 1/4"  deep. Prefers  hot weather.  Water  sparingly.

Seeds can  be  roasted and  eaten.  Seeds  also are a oil  crop. Residue  acts as a  nematode  repellent.   Plant 8"-10"  apart 1/2"  deep.

Grows well in  poor soil  without much  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked; eat  leaves  cooked.

Likes 500mm  rain/yr.,  <1000m,  frost-free  subtropics.  Uses: fuel,  crop shade,  animal fodder  (although  intake sd. be  <30% of dry  matter, due to  toxic factors).  Might kill any  one- stomached  animals.

Quick-growing  shrub  produces  firewood in 6  months.   Adapted to  difficult  (saline,  alkaline, wet)  soils. Stems  used for fiber;  weed  supressant;  windbreak;  green manure;  cover crop;  erosion  control;  fodder.
Striga- resistant  sorghum  developed at  Purdue (Line  92042).

Quick-growing  shrub  produces  firewood in 6  months.   Adapted to  difficult  (saline,  alkaline, wet)  soils. Stems  used for fiber;  weed  supressant;  windbreak;  green manure;  cover crop;  erosion  control;  fodder.
More adapted  for northern  climate than  other  sorghums.  Grown for  syrup  produaction.
About 28 to  reach  maturity; roots  are bright red  and globe  shaped. Older  roots tend to  get pithy.  Strong tops  for upland soil.  Good for  bunching and  shipping.

Perennial  forage legume  useful as hay,  silage,  nitrogen  fixation for soil  improvement  and erosion  control. Plant  in well-drained  soil with pH  >5.5. Seedling  growth is  slow, so  control  competing  weeds until  stylo reaches  4 inches  height. this  variety has  erect/  creeping  growth habit.
A  white-skinned  radish, also  known as  Japanese  radish.  Generally  larger,  courser, and  later to mature  than other  radish  cultivars.  Roots can be  grated and  eaten raw or  cooked.
Young leaves  and flower  pods are also  edible and  young  seedlings can  be cooked like  spinach.

Used in  highland alley  farming,  adapted to  saline, arid,  wet, or acidic  conditions.  Grows fast;  short-lived  shrub; stems  used in  construction;  flowers,  leaves edible;  seeds a  famine food  (soak 3 days).

A medium  sized  nitrogen-fixing  tree used in  alley cropping,  for fuel wood,  as a crop  shade, and  wind break.  Tolerates acid  soil. Grows  best in areas  with >1000mm  annual rainfall  and mean  temp. >20C.
60 in. rain.  Wide soil  tolerance,  can't do heavy  grazing,  vigorous  aggressive.  This var. likes  high rain and  altitude.

A medium  sized  nitrogen-fixing  tree used in  alley cropping,  for fuel wood,  as a crop  shade, and  wind break.  Tolerates acid  soil. Grows  best in areas  with >1000mm  annual rainfall  and mean  temp. >20C.
Hardy  perennial to  2m tall;  drought hardy.  Not frost or  flood tolerant;  800mm mean  rain. Very late  flowering,  adapted to  infertile soils.
A selection  shown to have  high yields  compared to  other  accessions of
Sesbania in  Australia. Use  for organic  matter or  nutritious  fodder.

Sow seeds 1"  deep. After 1  year  transplant to 3'  apart. Wait 2  years before  pulling stalks  for eating and  cut seeds that  develop near  the ground.  Do no eat the  leaves, as  they can  contain toxic  amounts of  oxalic acid.
Hardy  perennial to  2m tall;  drought hardy.  Not frost or  flood tolerant;  800mm mean  rain. Very late  flowering,  adapted to  infertile soils.
Quick-growing  shrub.  Adapted to  difficult  (saline,  alkaline, wet)  soils. Stems  used for fiber;  weed  supressant;  windbreak;  green manure;  cover crop;  erosion  control;  fodder;  fuelwood.
Soft woody  hery or small  tree grown in  the tropics up  to 2100m. No  pretreatment  needed. Plant  seeds 1. 5-2cm deep.  Tolerant to
drought,  strong wind,  grazing and  repeated  pruning.

Tree to  15m(50 ft)  tall  and 30 cm (1  ft) in diameter,  with an  irregular open  crown. Widely  planted as a  shade tree, in  shelterbelts,  and in  fuelwood  plantations.  Fast growing  and tolerant of  adverse  conditions.

Trim wings or  plant fresh.  Plant 1.5-2cm  deep. Thrives  in sandy soils  with moderate  rainfall.  Common as a  shrub or bush  (6-9m). Useful  for  reforestation,  medicinal  properties,  and general  purpose  wood.
Cover crop.  Scarify seeds  by placing on  cloth and  rolling a hard  object over  them. Soak 24  hours; keep  moist but not  too wet. Plant  1/2 inch deep.  Germinates in  about 15  days.
Native to Near  East & China;  very  drought-resist.  tol. of soil  salinity &  alkalinity; bird  damage
common.  12-14%  protein.  stalks  for forage &  fuel. Grown in  clumps or  rows.
Native to Near  East & China;  very  drought-resist.  tol. of soil  salinity &  alkalinity; bird  damage  common.  12-14%  protein.  stalks  for forage &  fuel. Grown in  clumps or  rows.

Not a true  spinach, but  similar in  flavor when  cooked. Plant  seeds in row  16-20 inches  apart; thin to  4-6 inches  apart in the  row. Heat  resistant.  Plants reach  1-2 ft in  height, but are  heavily  branched,  spreading out  2-3 ft across.
Chia seed  may be eaten  raw as a  whole seed  and is an  excellent  source of  omega-3 and  dietary fiber.
Hybrid. Plants  are  well-branched,  semi-early,  and prolific  with 2-3 fruits  per node.  Harvest  begins 50-55  days after  transplanting.
Purple-reddish  fruits are short  and chubby  with tender  white flesh.
78-90 days  vigorous,  erect plants  with glossy  dark  purple-black  fruits. Long  harvest  season.  Resistant to  Phomopsis  blight and fruit  rot.
Sphere- shaped fruit  with uniform  appearance  and almost  black skin.  Plae green  flesh.  Vigorous  growth;  harvest begins  50-55 days  after  transplanting.
Plants are  small, stout,  and compact.   Bears 2-3  fruits per  cluster.  Fruit  slender,  straight, 20cm  long and  3.5cm in  diameter.   Purple skin  with white  stripes.  White  flesh.
Very  productive in  hot, humid  weather. May  grow as a  medium sized  shrub.  Beautiful long,  white frutis  with white  flesh.
Fast-growing,  spiny  evergreen

shrub. Growth  up to 15m.  Tolerates  drought,  salinity, and  waterlogged  soil  conditions.  Living fence,  fodder, fuel,  construction  materials, and  edible fruit.  Dehull seeds,  soak in hot  water  overnight.
Very  productive in  hot, humid  weather. May  grow as a  medium-sized  shrub.  Beautiful,  long, purple  fruits with  white flesh.
Open  pollinated  silage corn  variety  developed by  the University  of Florida.  Selected for  high  yield and  nutrient  content.  Grows to a  height of 3  meters.
Compact,  erect plant  with small,  delicate,  cream-type  peas.   Reisistant to  lodging. 15 cm  yellow pods at  fresh-shell  stage.
Very  productive in  hot, humid  weather. May  grow as a  medium-sized  shrub.  Beautiful,
long, purple  fruits with  white flesh.
Very  productive in  hot, humid  weather. May  grow as a  medium-sized  shrub. Fruit  green until  yellow when  mature.  Productive at  ECHO even  with  nematodes.

A single cross  sweet corn  hybrid  developed in  Hawaii,  especially for  the tropics.  Plant in  isolation  (20m) to  reduce  contamination  by non-sweet  pollen that  could make  corn kernels  starchy.
Resistant to  the cowpea  curculio and  root-knot  nematodes.   Tall, upright  plant.  Pods  are slightly  curved, 17-20  cm long.   Plants may  produce a  second crop.
The fruits are  bright orange,  thick-skinned  and have  greenish pulp  of a very  refreshing,  subacid flavor  that has been  likened to a  combination of  orange,  pineapple and  tomato.
Andean South  America,  cultivated.
Resistant to  root knot  nematode.  Upright  growth, 24  inch yellow  pods at  fresh-shell  stage.  Kidney  shaped,  cream colored  pea with small  black eye.
Open- pollinated  sweet corn  developed by  the University  of Hawaii with  75% tropical  parentage.  White kernals;  related to  'Hawaiian  Supersweet  #9" with have  yellow  kernals.
Forage plant;  originated in  Mali.   Drought- tolerant.  Plant  seeds about 2  cm. deep.

Popularly  known as  broad-leafed  African  nightshade,  normally has  ovate leaves  with large  purple berries  and it is not  bitter.  Typically  collected from  the wild, but is  increasing in  popularity as a  kitchen  garden  species.
Forage plant;  originated in  Mali.   Drought-
tolerant.  Plant  seeds about 2  cm. deep.

110 day corn.  Stays less  than 7 feet  tall, produces  1-2 ears. Best  grown with  manure. Red  kernals with  white spots.  Dries well,  makes good  flour. Also  good for  chicken or pig  feed.

Medium,  early- maturing.  Produces  round-oval,  medium to  large tubers of  uniform  shape,  shallow eyes,  white skin,  cream/white  flesh. Thrives  at 4500 feet  above sea  level.  Susceptible to  diseases in  tropics and  subtropics at  lower  elevations.

70 days.   High- producing  fresh market  pea. Excellent  flavor. Sow  3-6" apart in  rows 2-3 1/2  ft. apart.

Hope Seeds  Container  tomato;  Storng  producer of  4-6 oz good  quality red  fruit. Very  compact plant  can be grown  in 3-5 gallon  size  containers;  shows  promise for  both cool  short growing  areas as well  as warmer  climates.

About 68 days  to maturity.  Fruit is  cylindrical with  some taper  ends and has  uniform dark  green color.  Plant is  monoecious  with compact  vines.  Resistant/  tolerant to  cucumber  mosaic virus,  downy  mildew,  powdery
mildew and  scab. Open  pollinated.

About 68 days  to maturity.  Fruit is  cylindrical with  some taper  ends and has  uniform dark  green color.  Plant is  monoecious  with compact  vines.  Resistant/  tolerant to  cucumber  mosaic virus,  downy  mildew,  powdery  mildew and  scab. Open  pollinated.

Tropical  twining vine  with edible  seeds, young  leaves and  flowers.  Sow  in full sun and  moderately  fertile soil after  last frost,  about 6 seeds  per foot.  Trellis for best  growth. Thin  to 12 inches  when  seedlings  have their first  true leaves.  110-120 days  to bloom. Can  be grown as a  perennial in  zones 9 and  10.
Tropical  twining vine  with edible  seeds, young  leaves and  flowers.  Sow  in full sun and  moderately  fertile soil after  last frost,  about 6 seeds  per foot.
Trellis for best  growth. Thin  to 12 inches  when  seedlings  have their first  true leaves.  110-120 days  to bloom. Can  be grown as a  perennial in  zones 9 and  10.
Plan18-36 in  apart in rows  6 ft apart,  when soil is at  least 70 F (21  C). 110 days.  Harvest when  stems are dry;  light frosts will  not damage it  but a hard  frost will  damage fruits.
Plan18-36 in  apart in rows  6 ft apart,  when soil is at  least 70 F (21  C). 110 days.  Harvest when  stems are dry;  light frosts will  not damage it  but a hard  frost will  damage fruits.

Quick  maturing okra  on a short  plant. Use 2-3  seeds/hill on  18" rows or  hills. Plant will  begin  producing at  just over 1'  and reach a  height of  about 4' at  maturity.  Variety from  Hope Seeds;  originally from  Northern  India.
Hope Seeds  selection of  Prelude.
Earlier than  many  standard  types with a  shorter plants;  yields a good  quantity of  medium green  smooth  velvety pods.  Very  productive in  areas where  Clemson is  being used.

Asian variety.  Exceptionally  long pods, up  to 15 in length  at maturity.  Young fruit  may be  harvested up  to 3 in long for  fresh use. Tall  plant; use 3 ft  between rows.  Hope Seeds  variety  originally  obtained from  ECHO in 2002  and  maintained at  their Missouri  location;  re-acquired by  ECHO in  2013.

Long sweet  pepper, heavy  fruit set that  will benefit  from staking.  Mid-season  side-dressing  of calcium-rich  fertilizer in  deficient areas  will benefit  overall yield  and quality.  Donation from  Hope Seeds;  actual species  not known.
Tropical  yellow kernel  maize useful

for sileage  and feed,  should  perform well in  day-neutral  zones. If used  in more  temperate  zones the  plant will  aceive tall  green growth  but will not  bloom until  day length  shortens to 14  hours.  Advised to  plant about  30+ days past  past field corn  dates or after  wheat harvest  if desired for  green  stalk/sileage  feed.

Dark green  skin and deep  orange sweet  interior flesh.  Vigorous vine  requires  ample space  for optimal  growth. The  ground mark  will change  color from  light green to  cream to deep  orange  indicating  when the fruit  is best ready  for harvest.
Original strain  from Hungary  via Seed  Saver's  Exchange.  Selection is  uniform in  plant habit  and fruit  shape, earlier  and full of  flavor. Light  yellow fruit will  ripen to a
salmon color.  Extra-early at  70 days after  transplant.

Elongated bell  with good  yields of  10-14oz  thick-walled  fruit, ranging  from dark  green to red.  Plant will  benefit from  staking  because of  the good  yields of split  sets for  multiple  harvests.

Vigorous  spreading  bean will yield  split sets of up  to 8 pods per  set; thrives in  hot summer  conditions.  Young pods  may be  cooked like  green beans,  but more often  mature beans  are eaten as a  pulse. Also  used as  livestock feed.  Donation from  Hope Seeds,  accession  received from  Nigeria.
Short, very  leafy, immune  to rust & leaf
spot; grows in  infertile soil;  lacks prussic  acid &  glucoside.  Used strictly  for FORAGE-  not a grain  crop. Not  resistant to  downey  mildew.
Shrub tree up  to 25' tall.  Most  productive if  unpruned.  Fruits picked  when dark  red. Plant  seeds in  damp, well  drained,  potting soil,  germination  occurs within  3 to 4 weeks.
Shrub tree up  to 25' tall.  Most  productive if  unpruned.  Fruits picked  when dark  red. Plant  seeds in  damp, well  drained,  potting soil,  germination  occurs within  3 to 4 weeks.
Tropical  variety of  pumpkin. Sow  in well  drained, damp  soil after last  frost.
Tropical  variety of  pumpkin. Sow  in well  drained, damp  soil after last  frost.
Soak seeds  before  planting for  better  germination.

Sow in  well-drained  soil. 55 days.  Developed by  U. of  Arkansas.  Early  maturing,  tender- podded,  high-yielding  okra.  Compared to  Clemson  Spineless,  Jade has  darker green  pods, fewer  side branches,  higher yields,  and better  ability to  mature in late  plantings. 4'  plants.
Vigorous  perennial vine.  Does well in  hot and dry  climate. Use  tubers for fuel,  young fruits  and ground  seeds as food.   Plant 1" deep.
Vigorous  perennial vine.  Does well in  hot and dry  climate. Use  tubers for fuel,  young fruits  and ground  seeds as food.   Plant 1" deep.
Slow to bolt  Collards.  Tolerant to  both hot  weather and  cooler  temperatures.  Sow in well  drained,  damp,  composted  soil 1cm deep.  85 days.
Slow to bolt  Collards.  Tolerant to
both hot  weather and  cooler  temperatures.  Sow in well  drained,  damp,  composted  soil 1cm deep.  85 days.

African  Moringa  species.  Seems much  more drought  tolerant than  M. oleifera.  Bigger, more  tender leaves  year round. If  seed have  papery wings  still attached,  peel seed for  better  germination.

African  Moringa  species.  Seems much  more drought  tolerant than  M. oleifera.  Bigger, more  tender leaves  year round. If  seed have  papery wings  still attached,  peel seed for  better  germination.

Very hard  wood,  durable,  resistant to  rotting. Used  for  construction  and hand  tools. Grows  in very dry  locations.  Bark is a  source of  tannin.  Flowers  important  source of  nectar for  bees.  Valuable in
dune  stabilization  and recovery  for degraded  soils. Soak for  24 hrs before  planting, 2cm  deep in well  drained,  composted  soil.
Tropical carrot  variety which  sets seed in  one year.  Harvest crop  before seeds  set, but allow  a few plants to  go to seed.  Sow shallowly  and thin as  needed.
Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep next  to trellis.  Grows well in  poor soil  without much  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked; eat  leaves  cooked.
Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep next  to trellis.  Grows well in  poor soil  without much  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked; eat  leaves  cooked.
Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep near
trellis. Grows  well in poor  soil with little  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked; eat  leaves  cooked.
Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep near  trellis. Grows  well in poor  soil with little  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked; eat  leaves  cooked.

Tropical  evergreen  tree. Prefers  800 -1200 m  elevation.  Plant seeds in  shade in moist  soil. Usually  takes 1 to 2  months to  germinate.  Plant out into  deep  composted,  well drained  soil. Grafted  trees have  specific form  and fruit.
N
Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep near  trellis. Grows  well in poor  soil with little  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked; eat  leaves  cooked.
Selected for

bushier  growth.  Produces  more heavily  then other  oleifera  species. Eat  leaves like  spinach;  young pods  cooked like  asparagus.  Germinates  best in partial  shade. Pinch  the primary tip  at 1 m height;  pinch  secondary &  tertiary  branches  when 5-6 cm  long.
Hardy  perennial to  2m tall;  drought hardy.  Not frost or  flood tolerant;  800mm mean  rain. Very late  flowering,  adapted to  infertile soils.
Resistant to  the cowpea  curculio and  root-knot  nematodes.   Tall, upright  plant.  Pods  are slightly  curved, 17-20  cm long.   Plants may  produce a  second crop.
Slender vines,  drought- resistant;  needs  well-drained  soils; often  intercropped
with rice.   'Bush' variety  is shorter then  rice bean,  does not  require a  trellis.

column8: East India Walnut/  Woman's tongue  tree
column16: To improve  germination:  soak seeds in  cold water  24-36 hours  OR dip in  boiling water,  remove from  heat and let  soak another  3-5 minutes.
Short day  grano type  Hybrid. Very  high yielding  white onion  with good skin  quality.

Plant cuttings  upon  receving.  Push cuttings  into  well-drained  composted  soil and  transplant into  field later.  Arrows on  cuttings  should be  pointing  upwards  and/or lateral  buds should  appear on the  top side of  lateral branch  scars. Widely  adaptable to  full shade or  partial sun.  Grows best  with  high-rainfall in  well-drained  soil.
Take cuttings

out of  packaging and  plant  immediately  with arrows  pointing  upward in  well-drained  soil. Bury  each cutting  half way.  Leaves should  be boiled for  at least 5  minutes  before eating.  Do not eat raw  leaves.
A dark green,  strong, tall  and aromatic  annual plant.  Sow seeds in  well-drained  composted  soil 1cm deep.  plant out into  full sun in  rows 30cm  (12") apart.
Large, high  dome,  semi-erect  variety that  takes 65 days  to reach  maturity.   Widely  adapted and  easy to grow.   Heavy,  attractive  heads. Hybrid.
About 80 days  to maturity;  fruit reaches  2.25" length  and 1.25"  diameter;  early maturing  of extra-large  fruits that turn  bright orange;  scoville rating  of 200,000 to  350,000.
About 80 days  to maturity;  fruit reaches  2.25" length  and 1.25"
diameter;  early maturing  of extra-large  fruits that turn  bright orange;  scoville rating  of 200,000 to  350,000.
Brilliant red  color.  Bite-sized  grape  tomatoes with  great flavor  and high brix.
Leguminous  tree. Grows to  45 ft with  extensive  branching.  Little trunk  wood, lots of  foliage.  Scarify before  planting.

Hardy short  day plant  adopted to  dry, hot  conditions.  Disease- resistant,  high-yielding  lines. Not  frost-tolerant.  Rust, blight  resistant; wilt  tolerant. Plant  1/4" deep at 4"  spacing. Avoid  overwatering.
A fairly
slow-growing  shrub or small  tree, the  cattley guava  generally  ranges from  6.5 to 14 feet  tall, but the  yellow-fruited  may attain 40  ft.
55 days.Open  pollinated,  grown for  8-9cm  diameter  roots. Sow  seed 1cm  deep in  well-drained  damp soil.  Plant in rows  25 cm apart.  Full sun.
From Mexico.   Start seeds  1/4 inch deep  (in pots, or  direct seed)  and thin to 4-6  inches apart in  rows.
Use like a firm  summer  squash. Plant  1/2 in. deep in  mounds a few  feet apart.  Prefers trellis,  but not  essential.   Also known as  "wintermelon. "
Hardy  perennial to  2m tall;  drought hardy.  Not frost or  flood tolerant;  800mm mean  rain. Very late  flowering,  adapted to  infertile soils. I  CANNOT  FIND THIS  BULK BAG  -btl 3-2012
Originally bred  in Italy. 16"
long beans.  Prolific  producer. Sow  beans 1 cm  under soil,  7cm (3")  apart. Pick  beans every  two to three  days, and the  plant will  produce more.

Golden,  high-yield,  quality protein  (higher in  tryptophan  and lysine  than common  corn) variety  developed by  EMBRAPA  research  center. 63  days to  flowering.  Mean  productivity  5000 kg/ha.  Comes from  Brazil

Tropical  evergreen  tree. Prefers  800 -1200 m  elevation.  Plant seeds in  shade in moist  soil. Usually  takes 1 to 2  months to  germinate.  Plant out into  deep  composted,  well drained  soil. Grafted  trees have  specific form  and fruit.
For use as a  green  manure/cover  crop. GMCC.  Requires short  days to flower.  Scarify seed  before  planting. From
Honduras.  Brought to  ECHO in 2002  in two  installments,  the first by  Cheryl  Beckett.

Proprietary  Variety. Illegal  to multiply for  commercial  use without  express  written  permission.  Good for soils  with low  natural fertility.  Nitroflint  variety that  yields well in  low N  environments.  Mean yeild  when under N  stress 4000  kg/ha.
Soak seeds  overnight.  Cover with  1/4" soil, keep  moist. Cold,  heat, drought  and poor soil  tolerant  legume. Slow  growth but  hardy.

Deciduous  tree, grows up  to 30-60 m.  Foliage used  for fodder,  sometimes  used as  firewood,  good for  erosion  control and  reforestation.  Seed should  be left to soak  for 24 hours  before  planting.

Collected in  spring 2013.  From multiple  trees on  ECHO's  campus. Plant  seeds in flats  of well-drained  soil, seeds  should  germinate in  30 to 50  days.To  germinate,  soak for 24  hours then  keep in moist  soil for 30 to  60 days.  Harvest fruit  when slightly  soft and still  green. Eat as  a dessert fruit.  Commonly  known as  "chocolate  pudding" tree.
Collected in  spring 2013.  From multiple  trees on  ECHO's  campus. Plant  seeds in flats  of well-drained  soil, seeds  should  germinate in  30 to 50 days.

Soak seeds  overnight.  Plant in large  pots 5mm  deep in  well-mixed  topsoil,  compost, sand  (1:1:2). Keep  moist and  shaded.  Transplant at  30cm tall  to  well-drained  soil, full sun.  Vigorous and  prolific, with  red, sweet  flesh. Small  fruits typically  900-1000
Received from  Purdue  University.
Received from  Purdue  University.  Resistant to  Striga.
Received from  Purdue  University.
Received from  Purdue  University.  Original  packages  broke - two  Purdue lots  were  combined.

Also called  "Florida  cranberry"  Fresh calyx  (fleshy  structure after  the flower has  fades) used in  beverages,  sauces and  salads.  Leaves are  also edible.  Plant 1/2" (1  cm) deep and  3 feet apart.
Plant at a  shallow depth,  maintain moist  seed bed.  Cook and eat  young leaves  like spinach;  good yields of  yellow grain.
Plant seeds in  row 16-20
inches apart;  thin to 4-6  inches apart in  the row. Heat  resistant.  Plants reach  1-2 ft in  height, but are  heavily  branched,  spreading out  2-3 ft across.

Soak seeds  overnight.  Plant in large  pots 5 mm  deep in  well-mixed  topsoil,  compost, sand  (1:1:2). Keep  moist and  shaded.  Transplant at  30 cm to  well-drained  soil, full sun.  Self- pollinating.  Tolerant of  Papaya Ring  Spot Virus.  (PRSV) F1  Hybrid  originally from  Taiwan.
Heat-resistant;  Australian big  leaf lettuce  resistant to  bolting.  Resembles  cos lettuce  with yellowish  hue.
Tropical carrot  variety which  sets seed in  one year.  Harvest crop  before seeds  set, but allow  a few plants to  go to seed.  Sow shallowly  and thin as  needed.
Plant 1-2 ft.  Apart. Prefers  colder  temperatures,
but will  tolerate heat.
Sow seeds  1/2-1" deep,  about 8" apart  in fertile soil.  Prefers trellis.  Heat- tolerant.  Leaves eaten  raw or  cooked.
Long  production  season. HEAT  SCARIFY  seeds  pre-planting:  pour boiling  water over  seeds and let  cool 12 hours;  plant seeds  immediately,  1" deep.
Open- pollinated.  Plant seeds 1"  deep. Extra  long edible  pods that  grow up to  19".
Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep near  trellis. Grows  well in poor  soil with little  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked; eat  leaves  cooked.
Plant 1-2"  deep. Vines  vigorously,  Does best in  full sun.
Seeds should  be planted 1  inch deep and  1 inch apart in  rows 2. 5 feet   apart. Trellis.
Early,  disease- resistant  variety bears  solid, 3- to  4-lb. heads.  Compact  plant. 58 days.  Sow seeds  1cm deep in  well-drained  composted  soil. Full sun.

Selected for  bushier  growth.  Produces  more heavily  then other  oleifera  species. Eat  leaves like  spinach;  young pods  cooked like  asparagus.  Germinates  best in partial  shade. Pinch  the primary tip  at 1 m height;  pinch  secondary &  tertiary  branches  when 5-6 cm  long.

Giant  passionfruit  seed from  Larry Smoke  (former ECHO  student) in  Honduras.
Most purple  passionfruits  prefer mild  tropical  climates and  do not do well  in Florida's  heat. 'Purple  Possum' was  selected near  Homestead  FL for large
reddish-purple  fruits.  Susceptible to  nematodes  and root  diseases.  Warning: seed  may be quite  variable.

Plant  immediately  upon arrival.  Plant seed  close to  surface of  well-drained  potting soil.  Germinates  within weeks.  Bears fruit  within 3 to 6  years. Pick  fruit when fully  ripe to avoid  high latex  content.
MIX: 2 cups  08108-121E,  2 cups  81046-081E,  2 cups  Unaccessed  Dark brown  Farm seed. All lots were  from farm  seed, THIS  SHOULD  ONLY BE  SOLD TO  BOOKSTORE  domestic  sales only.
Tender young  pods and  peas are crisp  and sweet.  Often  combined rice  and beans to  make savory  dishes. Dried  beans are  used as a  pulse. Strong  and vigorous  plant used for
intercropping,  green manure,  and fodder.  Plant 1" deep  in well-drained  compost.  Transplant out  when 4" tall.  Full sun. 140  days.

Intermediate- day, hybrid  variety.  Slightly  flattened  yellow onion  has potential  for large size.  Maturity:  approx. 290  days if late  summer-sown  and wintered  over; 110  days if spring.  Best at 33-40  degrees  latitude.
See lot 071E
Green manure  cover crop.   Can be grown  as a cash  crop. #00753

Sweet,  creamy fruits  are highly  regarded as a  desert fruit in  the tropics.  Mostly eaten  fresh, but  sometimes  made into  sherbets, ice  cream, jellies,  preserves, or  a fermented  cider.  Germinate by  soaking in  water or  scarfiy.  CAUTION:  seeds are  TOXIC,  contains  anonaine.

The seed  usually takes  14-21 days to  germinate; a  pre-soak
period of 24  hours is  recommended  prior to  planting. Plant  in well-drained  soil. Irrigate  during bloom  and fruit set if  flowering  coincides with  the dry  season.

Sow seeds in  well drained  media or soil  in 50% shade  location.   Seeds  germinate in  one week with  warm  temperatures  and 2-3 weeks  with cool  weather.   Seedlings  have highly  variable fruit  quality.
Perennial  legume. Likes  to climb 4-5  feet. Very  drought- tolerant  legume used  as green  manure,  fodder. Small  leaves; not a  thick  groundcover.  Bright purple
flowers used  as dye.
Perennial  legume. Likes  to climb 4-5  feet. Very  drought- tolerant  legume used  as green  manure,  fodder. Small  leaves; not a  thick  groundcover.  Bright purple  flowers used  as dye.

A medium  sized  nitrogen-fixing  tree used in  alley cropping,  for fuel wood,  as a crop  shade, and  wind break.  Tolerates acid  soil. Grows  best in areas  with >1000mm  annual rainfall  and mean  temp. >20C.

A medium  sized  nitrogen-fixing  tree used in  alley cropping,  for fuel wood,  as a crop  shade, and  wind break.  Tolerates acid  soil. Grows  best in areas  with >1000mm  annual rainfall  and mean  temp. >20C.
Used for  shade,  windbreaks,  timber,  fuelwood,  alley cropping.
Thrives in  tropical to  sub-tropical  conditions.  Adaptable to  wide range of  rainfall. Grows  best in loamy  soil.

Native to East  Africa. Known  for yellow  blooms and  wood  products. Also  used for soil  erosion  control.  Upright,  evergreen tree  growing to 15  m. Germinate  in well-drained  composted  soil. Seeds  germinate in  15 to 30 days.  Drought  resistant.

Native to East  Africa. Known  for yellow  blooms and  wood  products. Also  used for soil  erosion  control.  Upright,  evergreen tree  growing to 15  m. Germinate  in well-drained  composted  soil. Seeds  germinate in  15 to 30 days.  Drought  resistant.

strong wind,  grazing and  repeated  pruning.  Leaves and  seeds used as  a  multipurpose  pesticide  (pound  leaves/seeds,  soak, filter,  make spray.  Soak seeds  24 hours  before  planting.  CAUTION:  leaves and  seeds contain  poison.

fodder.
Climbing  variety from  Lake Victoria.  Drought  resistant,  green manure  and cover  crop. Young  leaves and  immature  pods eaten  after boiling to  remove toxins.  Also used as  fodder.

Semi- decidious tree  up to10 m tall.  Does best in  low-lying  well-drained  composted  soil. Seeds  are toxic, juice  made from  leaves kills  small insects,  including lice.  Fruit are  mature when  turning yellow  brown. Prefers  humid climate,  not  drought- tolerant.

Nick before  sowing. Seeds  should have
boiling water  poured over  them followed  by soaking in  room temp  water for 24  hours. Plant  seeds 1.5-2  cm deep.

This lot from  Tanzania.  Nutritious  vegetable  tree. Eat  leaves like  spinach;  young pods  cooked like  asparagus.  Grate roots as  horseradish  subst. Cut  back to 1.5 m  for easy  harvesting.  Germinates  best in partial  shade.
"Special seed"  from Arusha,  TZ. Looks like  Mucuna
From Magu,  Tanzania.  Reported as  best local  variety from  Joel Wildasin.
Plant 1cm  deep in  well-drained  composted  soil. Grows  2-3' tall, is  erect and  spreading with  many large,  undulated  leaves on a
white stem.   Withstands  cold as well as  heat, and  adverse soil  conditions.  A  high yeilding  hardy type of  excellent  quality.

Plant seeds  2cm deep in  well-drained  soil. Large  seeded  garbanzo  bean resistant  to fusarium  wilt.  Developed in  central  California,  USA. Seeds  can be eaten  as a dry bean  or as a green  vegetable  when  immature.  Drought- tolerant.

Soak seeds  overnight.  Plant in large  pots 5 mm  deep in  well-mixed  topsoil,  compost, sand  (1:1:2). Keep  moist and  shaded.  Transplant at  30 cm to  well-drained  soil, full sun.  Self- pollinating.  Tolerant of  Papaya Ring  Spot Virus.  (PRSV) F1  Hybrid  originally from  Taiwan.

This is a high  yield Solo  Sunrise fruit.  The fruits are  larger on  average than  the Original  Solo Sunrise.  Fruit size  averages  between  525-565  grams. There  is increased  fruit uniformity  and a very  smooth skin.  There is some  tolerance to  virus and  fungus.
Red flesh,  Medium  sweet, Avg.  size 1.5 - 2.6  kg, Fruit sets  35-70cm, High  yield. Long  shipper, 66%  herm/33%  female, No  virus  tolerance.
The Linda  variety  produces a  fruit that is  pear shaped  like that of the  Hawaiian Solo  Sunrise. The  fruit is slightly  larger on  average than  the Hawaiian

Solo Sunrise  and there are  approximately  80 fruits on  the tree at the  time harvest  begins. The  fruit is very  sweet at  13.brix and  the flesh is  salmon pink in  color. The fruit  sets high on  the tree as  with the  Hawaiian Solo  varieties.  Production on  average is  about 90 tons  per hectare  and the trees  typically flower  45 to 50 days  after  transplant into  the field. This  variety had a  gender of 66%  hermaphrodite  and 33%  female.

Red Flesh,  Selection from  Red Maradol,  Very uniform  fruit, Excellent  interior quality,  Uniform yield.  Developed for  export, Avg  size: 1.5-2.5  kgs, 66%  herm/33%  female, No  virus  tolerance.

This variety  has Red/Pink  fleshed fruit  averaging 400  - 500 grams of  weight. Fruit is  sweet and has  a firm outer  shell, which is  very good for  long shipping.  Fruit sets at  average 1  meter above  the ground.  Hermaphrodit e fruit is pear  shaped, with a  small neck at  the stem end.  The Taiwan  Sunrise fruit is  derived from  the original  Hawaiian Solo  Sunrise.
Large,  extremely  productive  green/yellow  sweet bell  pepper.Plant  1cm deep in  well-drained,  composted  soil. Resistant  to tomato leaf  spotted wilt  virus. Hybrid.
Large,  extremely  productive  green/yellow  sweet bell  pepper.Plant  1cm deep in  well-drained,  composted  soil. Resistant  to tomato leaf  spotted wilt  virus. Hybrid.
Widely grown  with high  tolerance to  heat. Heavily  warted, green,  6-9" fruits.  Also referred  to as "Round."
Open  pollinated,  determinate  red roma. 75  days to  maturity. Sow  1 cm deep in  well-drained  composted  soil. Disease  Resistant.
Plants are  small, stout,  and compact.   Bears 2-3  fruits per  cluster.  Fruit  slender,  straight, 20  cm long and  3.5 cm in  diameter.   Purple skin  with white  stripes.  White  fleshed.
Lablab is an  excellent  forage and  ground cover.  Does well in  humid regions  but is fairly  drought  resistent as  well.  Whte  flowers with  buff or light  brown seeds.

60 days. A  much  improved  Vates  selection.  Dark green  and large, the  cabbage-like  leaves retain  their eating  quality up to 2  weeks longer  than other  Vates types.   Plant 1cm  deep in  well-drained  composted  soil.

column10: Patissons  Panache  Jaune et Vert  Scallop

column16: Bright  blue-green.   Aromatic and  flavorful.  Use  fresh or dried.
Produces  large, round,  smooth light  brown seed  (Kabuli type)  approximately  4.5 months to  first harvest.  Packet: 16 g

Attractive  annual shrub,  also known as  False Roselle.  Use leaves in  salads, flower  calyxes (when  closed) used  to color juices,  sauces and  jellies. Plant in  spring in  deep, loose  soil. 1 m  apart, 1 cm  deep.
Climbing vine  10-15 ft long.  Eat like  zucchini when  young. Use  dried fruit as  sponge.  Flowers and  buds eaten  boiled. Plant  about 1/2 in.
deep, 6 ft  apart.
Selected for  early  flowering, high  seed yielding  ability and dry  matter  production.  Good forage  and ground  cover. Does  well in humid  regions but is  fairly drought  resistant as  well.
Tomato  develped by  the University  of Florida that  tolerates heat  and humidity.  Produces firm,
red, medium-  to large-sized  fruit. Resistant  to Fusarium  wilt (races 1,  2, and 3),  verticillium wilt  (race 1) and  gray leaf spot.
Good source  of seed oil,  rich in epoxy  acid used to  make plastics  and protective  coatings.   Requires short  days to flower.
Medium sized  tree used as  fodder and  firewood. Max  30m in height  and 3040 cm  in diameter.  Soak seeds  before  planting.

Flowers  regardless of  day-length.  Scarify  (nick/scrape)  seed coat  before  planting. Plant  1" deep near  trellis. Grows  well in poor  soil with little  water. Eat  young pods  raw or  cooked. Eat  leaves  cooked.  Tubers are  also edible.
Sow seeds in  well drained  media or soil  in 50% shade  location.   Seeds  germinate in  one week with  warm  temperatures
and 2-3 weeks  with cool  weather.   Seedlings  have highly  variable fruit  quality.

Plant 3-4m  apart in  well-drained  but moist, rich  soil; use  trellis.  Pollinate by  hand using  flowers from  two different  plants to get  fruit. This  passionfruit  can tolerate  somewhat  warmer  climates than  its purple  cousin.
Named after  the district  where it is  common and
was collected  by ECHO.  A  drought  resistant  green manure  cover crop.   Usually relay  cropped with  maize.  The  mature seeds  are sold and  processed as  a snack food.
Vigorous  perennial vine.   Tolerates  dryness.  Use  tubers for fuel,  young fruits  and ground  seeds as food.   Plant 1" deep.

Must be  planted within  3-4 weeks of  harvest.  Fast  growing and  tolerant of hot,  dry climates.  Twigs, leaves  and seeds can  be used in  many ways  due to their  pharmaceutic al and pest  control  properties.

Must be  planted within  3-4 weeks of  harvest.  Fast  growing and  tolerant of hot,
dry climates.  Twigs, leaves  and seeds can  be used in  many ways  due to their  pharmaceutic al and pest  control  properties.
From Mexico.  Start seeds  1/4 inch deep  (in plots, or  direct seed)  and thin to 4-6  apart in rows.
Annual herb.  Good green  manure. Bark  used as  source of  fiber. Mildly  toxic to cattle.  Dry pods  scare  monkeys out  of gardens.  Plant 1/2-1"  deep.

Plant grows  2-3' tall, is  erect and  spreading with  many large,  undulated  leaves on a  white stem.   Withstands  cold as well as  heat, and  adverse soil  conditions.  A  high yeilding  hardy type of  excellent  quality.

Also called  "Florida  cranberry"  Fresh calyx  (fleshy  structure after  the flower has  fades) used in  beverages,  sauces and  salads.  Leaves are  also edible.  Plant 1/2" (1  cm) deep and  3 feet apart.

Fast-growing  shade tree  with sweet,  red, berry-like  fruit.  To plant,  place seeds in  container of  water, stir until  seeds  separate, and  sprinkle over  soil.  Keep soil  moist and thin  seedlings  once  germinated.  Transplant  when 5-6  inches tall.

column10: Uberlandia x d  Or (LR Surrey  x HCM)

column16: Plants are  vigorous,  prolific and  medium-tall.   The petioles  are green with  occasional  purple stripes.   Pods are  five-ridged,  shiny dark  green, and  spineless.

Also Dead-Rat  tree or Upside  Down Tree.  fruit is 15 to  20  centimeters  long and is as  high in  calcium &  vitamin C as  an orange.  The seeds  produce  edible oil.  Typically grow  as solitary  individuals  and pollinated  by fruit bats.

Take cuttings  out of  packaging and  plant  immediately  with marker  arrows  pointing  upward in  well-drained  soil. Bury  each cutting  half way.  Leaves should  be boiled for  at least 5  minutes  before eating.  Do not eat raw  leaves.
Very tasty  fruits.  Grows  in cool tropics,  1500 m at  equator.  Requires  close  management  (hand  pollination).  Needs  1200mm rain  during  growing  season.

Plant grows  2-3' tall, is  erect and  spreading with  many large,  undulated  leaves on a  white stem.   Withstands  cold as well as  heat, and  adverse soil  conditions.  A  high yeilding  hardy type of  excellent  quality when  cooked.

Plant cuttings  upon  receving.  Push cuttings  into  well-drained  composted  soil and  transplant into  field later.  Arrows on  cuttings  should be  pointing  upwards  and/or lateral  buds should  appear on the  top side of  lateral branch  scars. Widely  adaptable to  full shade or  partial sun.  Grows best  with  high-rainfall in  well-drained  soil.

Fruiting vine.  Plant 3-4  meters apart.   Requires  cross- pollination and  may need  hand  pollination.  Scratch seeds  on sandpaper  before  planting to  improve  germination.

Prefers a  cooler climate  than yellow  passionfruit.  Produces  smaller but  generally  sweeter fruit  than yellow  variety.  Plant  3-4 meters  apart.   Requires  cross- pollination and  may need  hand  pollination.

To germinate,  soak for 24  hours then  keep in moist  soil for 30 to  60 days.  Harvest fruit  when slightly  soft and still  green. Eat as  a dessert fruit.  Commonly  known as  "chocolate  pudding" tree.

Sweet,  creamy fruits  are highly  regarded as a  desert fruit in  the tropics.  Mostly eaten  fresh, but  sometimes  made into  sherbets, ice  cream, jellies,  preserves, or  a fermented  cider.  Germinate by  soaking in  water or  scarfiy.  CAUTION:  seeds are  TOXIC,  contains  anonaine.
